{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17642458","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17642458"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:40:09+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:40:09+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17942"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17942","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17942"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.2,0.25,0.05,0.45,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10656"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78678"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10656","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10656"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17942"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64021"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"7260"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24824"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24826"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78678","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78678"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following landmarks of the occipital bone contains the clivus?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Foramen magnum","External occipital protuberance","Occipital condyles","Basilar part","Hypoglossal canal"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clivus is a sloping bony surface located in the \u003Cstrong\u003Ebasilar part\u003C/strong\u003E of the occipital bone. It forms the anterior portion of the foramen magnum and slopes upwards towards the dorsum sellae of the sphenoid bone. This area is a site where lesions can occur, affecting nearby structures such as the brainstem and cranial nerves.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe spinal cord traverses through the \u003Cstrong\u003Eforamen magnum\u003C/strong\u003E. It does not contain the clivus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eexternal occipital protuberance\u003C/strong\u003E is a bony prominence on the outer surface of the occipital bone, serving as an attachment point for the nuchal ligament.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eoccipital condyles\u003C/strong\u003E are rounded projections on either side of the foramen magnum that articulate with the atlas of C1, the first cervical vertebra.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ehypoglossal canal\u003C/strong\u003E is a passageway in the occipital bone for the hypoglossal nerve (cranial nerve XII). It is not located in the basilar part and does not contain the clivus.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The clivus is located in the basilar part of the occipital bone.","Understanding the anatomy of the occipital bone is crucial for interpreting cranial imaging and surgical planning."],"references":["Singh, V. (2023). Textbook of Anatomy-Head, Neck and Brain, Volume III-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Patestas, M. A., \u0026 Gartner, L. P. (2016). A textbook of neuroanatomy. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Patel, C. R., Fernandez-Miranda, J. C., Wang, W. H., \u0026 Wang, E. W. (2016). Skull Base Anatomy. Otolaryngologic clinics of North America, 49(1), 9\u201320. https://doi.org/10.1016/j.otc.2015.09.001","Anderson, B. W., Kortz, M. W., Black, A. C., \u0026 Al Kharazi, K. A. (2023). Anatomy, Head and Neck, Skull. In StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64021"}